00:35:03.859 --> 00:35:06.960
parole if you don't keep yourself monitored.
You could

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:12.619
be sent back to jail
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Can it be stipulated beyond parole?

00:35:12.619 --> 00:35:14.999
&gt;&gt; Russell: You mean the anklet?
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Yeah?

00:35:14.999 --> 00:35:18.730
&gt;&gt; Russell: There are places where legislators
are

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:30.820
trying to make it a life time form of surveillance,
yes. And no -- I mean there are challenges,

00:35:30.820 --> 00:35:36.119
you
know, to the constitutional rights of people

00:35:36.119 --> 00:35:40.359
regarding the sentencing of sex offenders.
In all

00:35:40.359 --> 00:35:50.940
parts of the country. It's an easy political
platform to run on in this country. And -- because

00:35:50.940 --> 00:35:55.450
everybody's afraid of sex offenders in ways
that are

00:35:55.450 --> 00:35:59.100
almost taboo to think about -- to examine.
Just

00:35:59.100 --> 00:36:03.950
kind of blanket way. And, you know, without
making

00:36:03.950 --> 00:36:10.119
any distinctions or discriminations or getting
up

00:36:10.119 --> 00:36:12.109
close enough to understand the differences
--

00:36:12.109 --> 00:36:15.990
different types of sex offense, different
conditions

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:20.359
that lead someone into it, and different degrees
of

00:36:20.359 --> 00:36:24.950
disturbance that bring someone to it, and
we decided

00:36:24.950 --> 00:36:29.220
lumping this whole population together once
they're

00:36:29.220 --> 00:36:33.549
out of jail. You know, I've done some talk
shows

00:36:33.549 --> 00:36:37.700
while I'm doing this tour. Call-ins, radio
call-in shows,

00:36:37.700 --> 00:36:40.869
and some people -- they haven't read the book
--

00:36:40.869 --> 00:36:43.020
that's necessarily the first question I ask
when

00:36:43.020 --> 00:36:48.430
they come in swinging like that. They call
in, and they say

00:36:48.430 --> 00:36:51.789
"You're just justifying the offender, the
perp and

00:36:51.789 --> 00:36:54.150
blaming the victim." I said, well, have you
read

00:36:54.150 --> 00:36:56.769
the novel?" And they say, "No, and I'm not
going to

00:36:56.769 --> 00:37:06.239
either. I think these people should be executed."
They really mean it. They're not kidding.

00:37:06.239 --> 00:37:09.569
There's
no discussion of course with anyone like that.

00:37:09.569 --> 00:37:11.690
Brings anger and agenda. And they usually
identify

00:37:11.690 --> 00:37:16.319
themselves as a victim of sexual crime. And
what

00:37:16.319 --> 00:37:20.950
can you say to that? All I can say, "Well,
it's a

00:37:20.950 --> 00:37:23.559
novel, and it doesn't blame the victim in
any case.

00:37:23.559 --> 00:37:26.011
And you really have to kind of read the novel
to see

00:37:26.011 --> 00:37:30.019
that and understand that." But then I've walked
into kind of a defensive position that I don't

00:37:30.019 --> 00:37:36.820
want
to be in. But there's a movement afoot all

00:37:36.820 --> 00:37:41.490
across
the country to basically make it a life sentence.

00:37:41.490 --> 00:37:44.500
&gt;&gt;Male #2: How do other countries deal with
this?

00:37:44.500 --> 00:37:48.019
Other cultures?
&gt;&gt; Russell: As far as I know, there's nothing

00:37:48.019 --> 00:37:52.190
like the
American panic over sex offender. In Europe,

00:37:52.190 --> 00:37:56.289
Canada -- just this morning I spent an hour
on the

00:37:56.289 --> 00:37:59.930
radio talking to CBC journalist talking about
it.

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:06.839
She was comparing Canadian approach to American
approach which is far less punitive and makes

00:38:06.839 --> 00:38:12.940
much sharper distinctions and doesn't have
this ongoing after. She was sort of shocked.

00:38:12.940 --> 00:38:15.309
"Is
it really true you can go online and you can

00:38:15.309 --> 00:38:17.950
go to
your own block and your own neighborhood and

00:38:17.950 --> 00:38:21.069
locate any
convicted sex offender who may have been convicted

00:38:21.069 --> 00:38:24.260
ten
or 20 years ago." Yeah, it's there. Just do

00:38:24.260 --> 00:38:28.690
it; try it. It's really
amazing and she couldn't believe it.

00:38:28.690 --> 00:38:33.759
&gt;&gt;Male #3: I think just a follow up. I think
in

00:38:33.759 --> 00:38:36.140
Italy, they punish the sex offenders by reelecting
them. [laughter]

00:38:36.140 --> 00:38:42.069
&gt;&gt; Russell: Yeah, to higher office.
&gt;&gt;Male #3: I want to ask what your writing

00:38:42.069 --> 00:38:48.339
process is
like. How do you go about crafting a significant

00:38:48.339 --> 00:38:53.080
novel?
&gt;&gt; Russell: Well, umm -- it varies somewhat

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:56.920
of course
from book to book. In this case, when I was

00:38:56.920 --> 00:38:59.250
describing how I kind of accumulated mass
of

00:38:59.250 --> 00:39:04.289
material that without a real intention at
the time,

00:39:04.289 --> 00:39:06.609
at first anyhow, to write a novel about it
I didn't

00:39:06.609 --> 00:39:08.420
know what I was going to do with it. I was
just

00:39:08.420 --> 00:39:11.640
trying to satisfy my own curiosity and try
to

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:14.700
understand a phenomenon that I couldn't look
away

00:39:14.700 --> 00:39:18.940
from any longer and so on. And then the Kid
emerged -- the character -- I began to imagine

00:39:18.940 --> 00:39:23.470
the
kid like that. Not based on anybody. It was

00:39:23.470 --> 00:39:27.089
easy
for me to imagine a kid going into that circumstance

00:39:27.089 --> 00:39:31.700
getting locked into a kind of shadowy world
on the

00:39:31.700 --> 00:39:36.470
edge of sex offending because of pornography
and

00:39:36.470 --> 00:39:39.599
addiction to pornography and losing track
of his own sex

00:39:39.599 --> 00:39:43.069
life. I mean, the Kid's a virgin. He's a convicted
sex offender who was a

00:39:43.069 --> 00:39:47.319
virgin, that was a first thing I wanted to
say But in terms of the actual process from

00:39:47.319 --> 00:39:51.210
what's
there. I tend to work with two outlines. One

00:39:51.210 --> 00:39:55.829
is
kind of an arc of a whole story and that is

00:39:55.829 --> 00:40:01.890
very
rough, very approximate. It's sort of as if

00:40:01.890 --> 00:40:02.890
I'm
saying, "Okay. I want to climb that mountain

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:06.220
and I
know it's east of here." That's about all

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:07.220
I know.

00:40:07.220 --> 00:40:08.220
[chuckles]

00:40:08.220 --> 00:40:09.809
Between here and there, I've got to go up
and down,

00:40:09.809 --> 00:40:12.099
through the valleys and through the forests
and

00:40:12.099 --> 00:40:14.430
foothills and so on to get there. But I'm
not sure

00:40:14.430 --> 00:40:18.980
where the trail is going to lead to get there.
I

00:40:18.980 --> 00:40:21.339
can see in the distance the peak at least.
And that

00:40:21.339 --> 00:40:26.160
large outline governs that direction. It's
like a

00:40:26.160 --> 00:40:30.030
compass really. And then, I tend to make a
short

00:40:30.030 --> 00:40:34.950
outline that only covers the next ten, 15
pages --

00:40:34.950 --> 00:40:37.529
next scene sequence is the way I think of
them. I

00:40:37.529 --> 00:40:42.500
tend to write in scenes. Visual -- episodes
that

00:40:42.500 --> 00:40:45.760
you can visualize the way you could with that
scene

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:49.609
with the Kid in the library. That's a scene.
And I

00:40:49.609 --> 00:40:56.180
tend to write chapters that seem to have evolved
over the years into three or four. Someone

00:40:56.180 --> 00:40:59.579
can do
an analysis on it better than I. Three, four

00:40:59.579 --> 00:41:02.990
scenes. And that's a fairly detailed outline.
Where I sort of know which

00:41:02.990 --> 00:41:05.400
scene follows what. After the library, I want
him

00:41:05.400 --> 00:41:10.570
to get back on his bike back on the Causeway
that's

00:41:10.570 --> 00:41:15.760
where we meet Iggy the iguana and one or two
of the other guys living under the Causeway

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:20.880
Take it to that.
And the scene where the night is falling.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:23.849
So that
will give us the physical surround of the

00:41:23.849 --> 00:41:26.710
place.
The city that surrounds it and the bay and

00:41:26.710 --> 00:41:31.720
all the rest of it. The socioeconomic part
too. So I can lay that out and then

00:41:31.720 --> 00:41:35.060
work with that. And be open at the same time
to

00:41:35.060 --> 00:41:38.440
developments that may come in along the way.
I

00:41:38.440 --> 00:41:41.230
might discover a character as indeed I did
when I

00:41:41.230 --> 00:41:45.059
wrote when he goes back under the Causeway
from the

00:41:45.059 --> 00:41:49.519
library this character shows up who's a shyster,
a

00:41:49.519 --> 00:41:53.829
really scary. Called the shyster because he
had

00:41:53.829 --> 00:42:01.880
been a lawyer and a state legislator who was
arrested for pedophilia and soliciting sex

00:42:01.880 --> 00:42:07.180
from little
girls in a sting operation. But I just brought

00:42:07.180 --> 00:42:09.630
him
in because I thought, "You know, I've got

00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:13.999
this kid
who -- yeah, he broke the law but we already

00:42:13.999 --> 00:42:18.289
kind of
sense it wasn't a big deal. He's not a pedophile.

00:42:18.289 --> 00:42:28.859
He's not a rapist. It's something else he
did wrong. We don't know what it is but it's

00:42:28.859 --> 00:42:30.769
not a big deal. But
there are guys down there who are serious

00:42:30.769 --> 00:42:32.190
criminals
or psychopaths or sociopathic. So I needed

00:42:32.190 --> 00:42:35.560
one. So
I brought him in. Suddenly he's there. This

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:38.309
guy is
really scary. Now he's there. I don't want

00:42:38.309 --> 00:42:42.079
to let
go of him. I want to keep him as kind of a

00:42:42.079 --> 00:42:46.980
weight
on things, develop the story in ways that

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:47.980
make him a
part of it, too. He's going to have someone

00:42:47.980 --> 00:42:48.980
in there
that's really evil. And so, he plays that

00:42:48.980 --> 00:42:51.279
role. It
goes like that. Then I have it, affecting

00:42:51.279 --> 00:43:03.339
the rest of it. One or two more?
Yeah, another question

00:43:03.339 --> 00:43:10.990
&gt;&gt;Male #4: [inaudible]
&gt;&gt;Russell: I can walk over from my place.

00:43:10.990 --> 00:43:20.799
Yeah, and I walk over and spend a little time
there.

00:43:20.799 --> 00:43:24.580
Not a lot. I wasn't doing any investigative
journalistic

00:43:24.580 --> 00:43:27.789
approach to it. I was doing it as a novelist.
What

00:43:27.789 --> 00:43:33.130
I wanted were the physical details of it.
I wanted

00:43:33.130 --> 00:43:35.109
to know what does it smell like and what does
the

00:43:35.109 --> 00:43:36.759
sound of the 24 hour rumbling cars overhead.
What

00:43:36.759 --> 00:43:38.880
is it like to be under metal and concrete.
Right

00:43:38.880 --> 00:43:43.989
there on the edge of the water -- the bay
-- tide

00:43:43.989 --> 00:43:50.840
going up and down. You know, trash coming
up out of

00:43:50.840 --> 00:44:10.739
the bay. Flotsam and jetsam, garbage and whatnot.
People throwing stuff off the Causeway as

00:44:10.739 --> 00:44:14.190
they
drive. Beer cans bouncing down. Stuff like

00:44:14.190 --> 00:44:16.720
that.
I mean, I wanted to see the physical details.

00:44:16.720 --> 00:44:19.059
And I
talked to some of these guys who were not

00:44:19.059 --> 00:44:21.920
adverse to
talking about their situation. Of course,

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:25.369
many of
them would especially plead their story and

00:44:25.369 --> 00:44:29.630
how innocent they are. What raw
deal they got. This that and the other thing.

00:44:29.630 --> 00:44:34.099
I
worked in prison before. I know how that goes.

00:44:34.099 --> 00:44:37.680
Nobody's guilty when you start talking to
people.

00:44:37.680 --> 00:44:41.130
But they weren't threatened by my being there.
They

00:44:41.130 --> 00:44:45.740
all felt as though they were being treated
very

00:44:45.740 --> 00:44:48.619
badly. I mean, one guy just kept repeating,
"Don't

00:44:48.619 --> 00:44:58.059
forget, we're not animals. We're not animals."
That was a cry. And I think he was speaking

00:44:58.059 --> 00:45:00.960
for a
lot of them. Yes?

00:45:00.960 --> 00:45:05.549
&gt;&gt;Male #5: How do you make decisions about
how many

00:45:05.549 --> 00:45:09.680
words you kind of dedicate to describing say
a city

00:45:09.680 --> 00:45:17.079
or, you know, describing like a person's physical
attributes. And how do you decide how much

00:45:17.079 --> 00:45:20.869
per
chapter per book you want to like dedicate

00:45:20.869 --> 00:45:23.410
to those
types of descriptions?

00:45:23.410 --> 00:45:26.509
&gt;&gt;Russell: That's an interesting question.
I can't

00:45:26.509 --> 00:45:34.950
say I can quantify it ahead of time in any
way. [chuckles] But I do know I

00:45:34.950 --> 00:45:41.640
use enough words -- I like phrasing it that,
it's an interesting question. I like enough

00:45:41.640 --> 00:45:47.150
words so I can visualize or hear what's being
said.

00:45:47.150 --> 00:45:53.400
If you're just talking about exposition, right?
Just descriptive language there.

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:58.000
&gt;&gt;Male #5: So that excerpt was a lot about
the city.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:00.430
Russell: A Yeah, surround. The world that
surrounds

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:07.499
him. And I wanted to see it as a writer, you
know?

00:46:07.499 --> 00:46:09.849
Visualize it. And so, I use enough so that
I could

00:46:09.849 --> 00:46:13.390
see it. I mean, I'm already familiar with
it. I

00:46:13.390 --> 00:46:16.279
see it every night there where the sun goes
down.

00:46:16.279 --> 00:46:24.820
But I wanted to really almost like mentally
photograph it for myself or film it as it

00:46:24.820 --> 00:46:30.799
were. And
I mean, Joseph Conrad, the great novelist

00:46:30.799 --> 00:46:31.799
wrote,
"Above all else, I want my reader to see."

00:46:31.799 --> 00:46:35.249
And he
meant not "understand," but literally see.

00:46:35.249 --> 00:46:39.259
Visualize it. I feel similarly. I want myself
to see first of all.

00:46:39.259 --> 00:46:42.989
Because in a sense what I'm doing here in
fiction is I'm

00:46:42.989 --> 00:46:47.490
creating visual and oral hallucinations. You
are

00:46:47.490 --> 00:46:54.380
seeing things that don't exist really
and you're hearing voices that are from another

00:46:54.380 --> 00:46:57.890
place. It's out of the body travel really.
When

00:46:57.890 --> 00:47:00.229
you're reading fiction if it's any good at
all, you

00:47:00.229 --> 00:47:03.109
forget where you are. You go into that world
and

00:47:03.109 --> 00:47:07.769
you start having visual and aural hallucinations.
I

00:47:07.769 --> 00:47:12.029
mean, dialogue is just that. People are talking.
There's no one in the room but you're hearing

00:47:12.029 --> 00:47:17.020
voices, if it's
any good, if it's good dialogue. And so, that's

00:47:17.020 --> 00:47:22.150
what I want to induce in
myself as a writer when I am writing. And

00:47:22.150 --> 00:47:25.299
then keep
on revising in that direction. And, if it

00:47:25.299 --> 00:47:29.109
works for
me, then it will work for a reader as well,

00:47:29.109 --> 00:47:33.400
I hope. I trust
that either both yourself and/or the reader

00:47:33.400 --> 00:47:38.730
will.
Okay. Well I think it used up the time. One

00:47:38.730 --> 00:47:39.830
more
question, sure.

00:47:39.830 --> 00:47:46.430
&gt;&gt; Male #6: Do you have someone who worked
to make it more compact, to

00:47:46.430 --> 00:47:52.079
change word order?
&gt;&gt; Russell: A I have a very good editor I've

00:47:52.079 --> 00:47:56.140
had for a
number of books already. And then, before

00:47:56.140 --> 00:48:00.119
him
similarly ten years. My editors either die

00:48:00.119 --> 00:48:08.460
or
retire [laughter] All of them -- I've had

00:48:08.460 --> 00:48:12.500
four editors over
the years that I work closely with -- and

00:48:12.500 --> 00:48:16.880
they all
work pretty much the same way. I write pretty

00:48:16.880 --> 00:48:23.539
cleanly myself. I go through the whole manuscript
at the end. We sit down at the table and they'll

00:48:23.539 --> 00:48:30.109
have a mark here and a mark there and turn
the page.

00:48:30.109 --> 00:48:31.109
Sometimes it will be a whole sentence "What
did you

00:48:31.109 --> 00:48:40.140
mean here? It seems kind of vague." Just poking
poking poking. And saying -- you know, forcing

00:48:40.140 --> 00:48:44.020
me
to look at it in a way I might not have otherwise

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:46.359
have
question myself. But no real heavy-handed

00:48:46.359 --> 00:48:50.980
editing . I never really had that. My first
editor

00:48:50.980 --> 00:49:00.660
was a great editor named Ted. Boy was he wonderful.
Great literary editor. And Ted used to do

00:49:00.660 --> 00:49:05.589
that and
go through it. You know, have the pages. Spend

00:49:05.589 --> 00:49:08.509
a
whole couple of days at my house or in our

00:49:08.509 --> 00:49:09.749
offices.
And, but every decision, every crossing, he

00:49:09.749 --> 00:49:13.329
would say,
"Don't forget, this is your book, not mine.

00:49:13.329 --> 00:49:19.499
And you're
only going to have -- you're maybe going to

00:49:19.499 --> 00:49:23.190
have ten
or fifteen books in your lifetime." I'm going

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:29.410
to have
ten or fifteen books that I edit every year

00:49:29.410 --> 00:49:32.190
or more. So this is
not my book; this is yours. So the responsibility

00:49:32.190 --> 00:49:35.839
also passed over to me. I said, "Wow, this
is

00:49:35.839 --> 00:49:39.700
right. I'm not going to have another one for
another three years. Better try to get it

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:41.380
as well done
as I can.

00:49:41.380 --> 00:49:46.960
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Do you give him a electronic copy?
&gt;&gt;Russell: Yes, I do. Everything is done -- we

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:51.849
don't
ship any paper anymore. And I work on the

00:49:51.849 --> 00:49:55.469
computer.
I write longhand still the first draft, because

00:49:55.469 --> 00:49:58.799
I
grew up writing in longhand and then working

00:49:58.799 --> 00:50:01.749
on a
mechanical typewriter. Getting a electrical

00:50:01.749 --> 00:50:06.799
typewriter is a big deal. I still have my
little Olympus portable or mechanical that

00:50:06.799 --> 00:50:12.220
I carried around with me in my teens and
twenties. And so, it sits like a monument

00:50:12.220 --> 00:50:13.640
in my office. [chuckles]
I couldn't use it today.

00:50:13.640 --> 00:50:24.540
&gt;&gt;Male #7: How much do you do that sort of
editing

00:50:24.540 --> 00:50:25.540
before you present the manuscript to the
editor?

00:50:25.540 --> 00:50:30.219
&gt;&gt;Russell: Quite a lot. I get it pretty refined
down. I go through dozens and dozens of drafts.

00:50:30.219 --> 00:50:35.289
Of
course, working, you know, on the computer,

00:50:35.289 --> 00:50:38.949
you can
revise endlessly and there are paragraphs

00:50:38.949 --> 00:50:45.329
-- places
in there where I have revised, it seems, endlessly.

00:50:45.329 --> 00:50:50.289
Go through
rapidly. But I turn the manuscript in, I'm

00:50:50.289 --> 00:50:53.910
pretty
convinced it's done. Except for a little bit

00:50:53.910 --> 00:50:59.849
of
this fine tuning that I mentioned earlier.

00:50:59.849 --> 00:51:02.079
Yeah.
Okay, guys, thank you all very much.

00:51:02.079 --> 00:51:02.349
[applause]

